<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>You Learned: View Source</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/style.css">
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/learn.css">
</head>
<body>
  <div class="learn-page">
    <img src="/images/logo.png" alt="EECS Girls Who Tech Camp" class="learn-logo">

    <div class="learn-hero">
      <div class="hero-icon">👀</div>
      <h1>Challenge 1 Complete!</h1>
      <p class="hero-subtitle">The Hidden Secret</p>
      <div class="flag-badge"><%= flag %></div>
    </div>

    <div class="learn-grid">
      <div class="learn-card skill-card">
        <div class="card-icon">🔍</div>
        <h2>Skill Unlocked</h2>
        <h3>View Page Source</h3>
        <p>Every webpage has source code anyone can read. HTML comments (<code>&lt;!-- --&gt;</code>) and hidden elements are <strong>never truly hidden</strong>.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="learn-card world-card">
        <div class="card-icon">🌍</div>
        <h2>Real World</h2>
        <h3>Security Reconnaissance</h3>
        <p>Researchers check source code for leaked API keys, internal URLs, and debug comments. A major airline once exposed customer data through comments left in production code.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="learn-card career-card">
        <div class="card-icon">👩‍💻</div>
        <h2>Career Path</h2>
        <h3>Penetration Tester</h3>
        <p>Companies pay ethical hackers to find vulnerabilities before the bad guys do. Curiosity is your greatest tool!</p>
      </div>

      <div class="learn-card key-card">
        <div class="card-icon">🔑</div>
        <h2>Key Takeaway</h2>
        <h3>Never Trust the Client</h3>
        <p>Anything sent to the browser — comments, hidden fields, CSS-hidden text — can be read by the user. Real secrets belong on the server.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="learn-nav">
      <a href="/" class="nav-btn secondary">← All Challenges</a>
      <% if (hasNext) { %>
      <a href="/challenge/<%= nextNum %>" class="nav-btn primary">Next Challenge →</a>
      <% } %>
    </div>
  </div>
</body>
</html>
